# Table IR Contract

When outputting tabular data (analysis, research, reports, etc.), use a structured
schema-driven representation. This applies to all table-like outputs regardless of
downstream renderer or execution mode.

## Format

```json
{
  "schema": {
    "columns": [
      { "key": "id", "label": "ID", "dataType": "number", "sortable": true, "filterable": false }
    ]
  },
  "data": [
    { "id": 1 }
  ]
}
```

## Column Schema (required fields)

| Field | Type | Description |
|-------|------|-------------|
| `key` | string | Unique field identifier |
| `label` | string | Human-readable column name |
| `dataType` | string | Semantic type (see below) |
| `sortable` | boolean | Whether renderer may enable sorting |
| `filterable` | boolean | Whether renderer may enable filtering |

## Supported dataType values

`number`, `string`, `text`, `date`, `datetime`, `boolean`, `url`, `enum`, `array`, `object`, `json`

## Rules

1. **Schema-first**: Separate column definitions from row data
2. **No pre-processing**: Return data in original order (unsorted, unfiltered)
3. **Complete data**: Include all rows; pagination is renderer responsibility
4. **Declarative**: All sorting, filtering, pagination handled outside the LLM
